  <!-- Section: Common Mistakes -->
  <section id="mistakes" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Applying Without Established Work History</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Slovenia specifically requires that you already work remotely, not that you plan to. Immigration checks documents carefully to verify ongoing work relationships. New freelancers with only a few months of history often face rejection. Build 6-12 months of track record first.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Showing Only Savings, Not Income</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Unlike some countries, Slovenia requires ongoing income proof—not just bank savings. You must demonstrate €3,200+/month coming in regularly, not a lump sum sitting in your account. Bank statements must show regular deposits from work.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Expecting Renewal</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Slovenia's DNV is for 12 months only, non-renewable. After the year ends, you must wait at least 6 months before reapplying. If you want continuous EU residence, consider other options like Portugal or Spain's renewable permits.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Weak Freelancer Documentation</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">For freelancers, authorities want to see contracts with clients, recent invoices, and proof of ongoing work. A vague statement that you "work online" isn't sufficient. Prepare comprehensive documentation of your client relationships.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Inadequate Health Insurance</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Short-term travel insurance won't meet Slovenia's 12-month residence permit requirements. Invest in proper annual international health insurance from the start. Attempting to patch together 90-day policies creates gaps and complications.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Healthcare in Slovenia -->
  <section id="healthcare" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Healthcare in Slovenia</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Slovenia has a high-quality healthcare system with both public (mandatory insurance for residents) and private options. DNV holders typically rely on international insurance for private care, which provides access to modern facilities throughout the country.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Healthcare Options</h3>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-6">
      <div class="border border-green-200 bg-green-50 rounded-lg p-6">
