  <!-- Section: FAQ -->
  <section id="faq" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What is the minimum income for Slovenia's digital nomad visa?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Slovenia requires approximately €3,200-3,300/month, which equals two times the average Slovenian salary. You must demonstrate ongoing income through bank statements and contracts—savings alone don't satisfy the requirement.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I renew Slovenia's digital nomad visa?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          No. Slovenia's DNV is for 12 months only and is not renewable. After your year ends, you must leave and wait at least 6 months before applying again. If you need continuous EU residence, consider Portugal or Spain's renewable options.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can my family come with me to Slovenia?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes, family members can accompany you if you demonstrate sufficient additional income to support them. Each family member needs their own health insurance, and the overall household income must cover everyone's living costs.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is Slovenia part of the Schengen Zone?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes. Slovenia is a full Schengen member and uses the Euro. Your DNV residence permit allows visa-free travel throughout the Schengen Area—perfect for weekend trips to Italy, Austria, Croatia, or beyond.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Do I need to already be working remotely to apply?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes. Slovenia requires proof that you are already actively working remotely—not just that you could work remotely. Immigration officers check for ongoing work relationships, recent projects, and steady income flow. New freelancers often face rejection.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How affordable is Slovenia compared to other EU countries?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Slovenia is more affordable than Western Europe (Austria, Italy, France) but slightly higher than Eastern Europe (Hungary, Romania, Bulgaria). Ljubljana costs roughly €1,800-2,400/month for comfortable living. The quality of life relative to cost is excellent.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Final Verdict -->
  <section id="verdict" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Final Verdict</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Slovenia's new Digital Nomad Visa (launched November 2025) offers something unique: access to one of Europe's most beautiful, safe, and livable countries. For nature-loving digital nomads who dream of Alpine peaks, turquoise lakes, and Mediterranean coastline—all within a 2-hour drive—Slovenia is hard to beat.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-4">
      The €3,200+/month income requirement is higher than some alternatives, and the 12-month non-renewable limit means this isn't a long-term settlement solution. But for a year of exceptional quality of life with Schengen access and central European location, Slovenia makes a compelling case.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-6">
      The main requirements to keep in mind: you must already be actively working remotely (this isn't for beginners), and you need comprehensive documentation of your work relationships. If you meet these criteria and value nature, safety, and quality of life over big-city nightlife, Slovenia could be your ideal EU base.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-primary-900 mb-3">Bottom Line</h3>
      <p class="text-primary-800 mb-4">
        Slovenia's DNV is perfect for established remote workers who prioritize nature access, safety, and quality of life. The €3,200/month income requirement targets higher earners, and the strict work verification means you need solid documentation. Budget €100-220/month for health insurance—essential for the visa and access to quality healthcare.
      </p>
